title: Vodafone Smart Speed Case - With Logo

description.text:
This is my first Thingiverse design. It is a phone case and I made it for my Vodafone Smart Speed 6 (VF-795).

The case is 1.5 mm thick, and has holes for the audio jack, main camera, flash, speaker, power button, volume rocker and charging port. The curves and corners are based off circles and cylinders that have a radius of 4 mm. In terms of measuring the phone's curvatures, I did not use digital calipers, only a basic 30 cm ruler, so I was forced to eyeball the sizes of the curves. It was a satisfying but painful build using OpenSCAD, made worse because I am a relatively a beginner.

For the final part I used Microsoft's built in app called '3D builder'. Although not recognised by Thingverse, this app is really good. I used it to put Vodafone's logo on the back.

I am yet to print this - which is why this thing is a 'work in progress' - I will soon be finished building my Prusa i3.

For long we wanted to do our own cold drip coffee, yet we didn't feel like spending few hundred euros for a new glass one. So I designed our own cold-dripper for new ways of exploring the coffee brewing craft.
For operation you need 1 flat paper filter and 1 60° paper filter you would use for classic V60 dripper (or any other paper filter you can fit in). The 60° filter goes to the coffee grind reservoir on the bottom and the flat one goes on top of your fresh coffee grind. If you have larger 60° filter you can easily make both out of it (or you can use both flat filters, it is up to you). And for sure you need a nicely roasted freshly grinded 50g of good coffee! The suggestion is 12 g of beans for 125 ml of water. The dripping speed should be around 1 per second.
So go ahead and have some!

title: 5V power outlet from USB charger - Arduino Projects PSU
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a very simple concept, it's basically a set of 4mm terminals wired to the end of a USB lead.

I had a bag of these cheap 4mm sockets http://www.aliexpress.com/item/50pcs-4mm-Banana-Panel-Socket-Test-Probe-Binding-Post-Nut-Plug-Jack-Connector/32563995312.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.72.OLMwwy knocking around, and I have a 4 amp USB wall charger. This thing basically provides the interface from USB power to 4mm sockets for banana plugs.

Assembly is hopefully self explanatory... Just wire the red and black wires out of the USB lead to the red and black 4mm terminals. Don't forget to test with a meter before trying to connect anything.

The back part was a loose fit when I printed it (I left a bit too much tolerance for the fit), it will hold in place on its own but doesn't have a firm snap - so adjust if this bothers you.

As a 'stretch goal' you could install an LED behind the 5V text on the front, the layers are thin enough to let some light through. Just wire across red/black along with a suitable resistor and you should have a power on indicator.

title: DIY Chalkboard Organizer from Old Windows

description.text: After we replaced the old windows in our house, I really wanted to find a way to repurpose some of the old windows, and especially the living room one, which had many panes. I spend a lot of time wondering what to do with the old frames, and finally I decided to make myself a chalkboard organizer, thanks to a suggestion made by my experienced window cleaners (http://www.paulswindowcleaningmelbourne.com.au/). We are a very busy family, with many lessons, meetings and trainings to attend, and unless we write everything down somewhere, we often forget and get confused. But thanks to the new chalkboard organizer, I just get up in the morning and look up to it. And everything I need to do today is right there in front of me. Here’s how I did it:

1. First you should get all the materials you will need. Here are they:
    • An old window frame with many panes
    • 1 plywood piece with the same dimensions as the window frame
    • Nails and a hammer
    • Chalkboard paint
    • 2 paint brushes
    • White paint
    • Sandpaper

  2. Now you should clean up the window frame, if there are any splinters and dangerous edges, use the sandpaper.

  3. Paint the entire frame with a white paint or some other colour you might find attractive.

  4. Use the chalkboard paint to paint one of the sides of the plywood.

  5. Once the window frame and the plywood piece are dry, you should get the piece of plywood, measure it once again, press it against the frame, cut our all the unnecessary parts, if there are any, and nail it to the frame. You should start from the back to the front, and use short nails, which won’t come out on the other side.

  6. If you’re creating a bigger organizer with the days of the week or the month, you can add small pieces of wood with the days painted on them. It will be an additional decoration and it will make your DIY chalkboard organizer even more interesting.

  7. When you’re done decorating, you can get the hammer and some nails and attach the organizer to the wall.

  8. You can create such chalkboard organizers in all shapes and with all kinds of panes, depends what you need in your home. Just have in mind that the chalk leaves white dust behind it, so you might consider putting something on the ground below it, to gather all the dust.

  9. Enjoy!

title: Keyholder with Loupe
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
There are a bunch of awesome key holders to print on this site (and others), and I have used on that was featured on thingiverse for a long time. But it broke recently, and I wanted one that would better fit my needs. So this is my take on the millions of swiss army key holders on thingiverse.

The USB is kind of a failed attempt at making a custom USB pen, and keeping this black and red theme. I uploaded it anyway...

What is different?

There where two things I really wanted in a everyday carry item, and that was a loupe!
I am taking a education as a machinist, and a lot of the time I need to focus on surface finish, burs and chamfers. So having a small loupe is quite handy. Even at home working with 3D prints having a loupe is a great idea. I have 4 different loupes in total :-) I like loupes...

Last I need a small knife... who doesn't?

You will need

2 x M3 Locknut (Needs to be a lock nut, otherwise it might unscrew itself)
2 x M3 bolt with 20mm thread and a head with a diameter below 12,5
(Optional)
1 x "30X Glass Magnifying Magnifier Jewelry Loupe" - Search it on ebay, it will be the first item listed most likely.
1 x Knife small enough to not stick out, AND to be legally carried where you live! I am not responsible for anything you do! Do your reasearch!

What I will use for mine Assembling the loupe. If you are not going to use a loupe, or just keeping the metal frame, you can skip this. I just used a pair of scissors to unscrew the little ring holding the glass, but you need to be careful not to scratch the glass! Carefully push out the small glass without touching it too much. <b>BE CAREFUL AROUND THE EDGES!!!</b> If you bought it from ebay, its must likely not the best of quality, so the edges may be <b>sharp!</b> Put it in between the printed case. If you want to you could add a small dip of glue, but screwing them together with the rest of the holder should hold them just fine. Done

The keyholder

Insert the loupe, keys and accessories. If you wont use a loupe, you can put more keys instead. Screw it all together and we are done! Make sure that the screw makes contact with the rubber in the lock nut, so that it wont unscrew it self over time.

Diese Halterungen ermöglichen die einfache Montage einer RP-SMA Buchse an z.B. der Fritz!Box 7490. Dies ermöglich die Anbringung von externen Wifi Antennen und steigert die Sendeleistung der Fritz!Box ungemein.

Auf dem Mainboard der Fritz!Box befinden sich ein oder zwei Antennen, welche mit einem Pigtail Stecker (IPEX) befestigt sind. Diese müssen mit einem Kunststoffwerkzeug -VORSICHTIG- entfernt und gegen IPEX auf RP-SMA Adapter getauscht werden. Der IPEX Stecker muss dafür von aussen durch einen Lüftungsschlitz nach innen geführt und vorsichtig am Pigtailstecker befestigt werden.

title: XYZ da Vinci filament cartridge spool replacement

description.text:
I designed this to be a direct replacement for the XYZ da Vinci filament spools inside their proprietary cartridges. I like to feed my printer from cartridges I refill myself because it keeps everything neat and contained and the stock cartridge assembly does a pretty good job of preventing intermittent self-unwinding and tangling that can occur with a simple exterior spool arrangement.

I left 6 square cutouts identical to the stock spools, so these should be compatible with your own filament winding apparatus if you have one (or if you'd like to use the drill-mounted one I designed, which I will upload next).

Printing my own extra spools lets me fill them with new filament while prints are ongoing. I also melted two of my original spools slightly by letting the oven get about 15C too hot while drying some filament. Oops.

Printed at 100% infill, each spool requires about 110g of ABS filament. The two halves are different and must be epoxied together. They are designed to be self-centering. I epoxied three together using some cheap Harbor Freight 2 part quick curing epoxy and had no problems.

As usual, use this design at your own risk, I am not responsible for any damages or injuries that may result from using these parts.

title: 3D printed RC truck rear axle - steel rod version

description.text:
UPDATE (11-august-2016) : DO NOT PRINT this thing, a much better version is now online. You can find it here - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1715175 .

This is a remix of the great work of MrCrankyface (http://www.thingiverse.com/MrCrankyface/about).

I wanted a more solid rear shaft, so I decided to use a 10 mm smooth steel rod (the one you use for 3D printers) instead of the 3D printed shaft.

I used a grinder to create chamfers on the steel rods, both in the ends and in the center area. The large gear has two M3 nuts on the inside, which allows the m3 screws to fix it on the rod. Same for the wheel hex, both sides.

To prevent the wheel hex to delamite for really large truck loads, I used some textile thread (black color, the cheap one you use to sew your pants), lot of layers, and some cyanoacrylate on top of the thread. You get an unbreakable material :)

I have also modified a bit the large gear so that the teeth are now connected to the center . This way the teeth are lot more strong as they are supported in one side.

You are welcome to make it better, in the zip archive you have all the Openscad source code.

description.text:
This is an Open Source Tablet Design that i cooked up really quickly. It Could be used to create a Tablet PC out of a Raspberry Pi 3 (which includes Bluetooth LE and WiFi). Though you'll probably need to desolder several things from the board if you want it to be thin as most modern tablets currently are. In this design you'll notice some oddities:

  1. No USB Ports (mice or keyboards through bluetooth, USB sticks aren't really needed when everything is cloud based)
  2. No Charging Port (Wireless Charging)
  3. Slots around the 4 quadrants of the bezel (act as acoustic cavity for better sound and Lights for system notification)
  4. No Front Facing Camera (for security reasons, scanning QR codes or taking pictures doesn't require this)

You will probably need to make some modifications depending on your touch screen panel (mounting holes will probably need to be adjusted) and the thickness of the tablet (depending the thickness of your SBC)

description.text:
This is a fan guard for the Flashforge Creator Pro 2016 and a remix of the Flashforge Dreamer fan guard by ff8jake.

This fan guard removes the need for the annoying tiny plastic spacers between the fan/screw and the original metal fan guard provided with the FFCP 2016, which does a poor job of protecting the fan.

With this design it is not possible to poke the allen key/wrench for the fan guard screws into the outer part of the guard where the fan blades are, providing better protection for your fan.

This version has the following changes from the design by ff8jake:

  • The screw threads fit through the holes without drilling
  • The space for the screw heads is bigger to fit the screws used on FFCP 2016
  • The top part of the guard fits into the holes at the top of the fan to make it more rigid

Update v3:

  • Uses a bit less plastic
  • More airflow
  • Slightly quicker to print

3D printing a sun-dial is a great way to learn about our solar system, and the history of astronomy (from the ancients like Aristarchus of Samos, through to Copernicus and Galileo). Our sense of time is determined by the spinning of the earth, and it changes depending on where we are in our orbit around the sun. A sundial is a time-telling device that is most closely linked to these cycles. The more the kid understands about the earth and the sun, the better they will be able to place it more accurately (parallel to the Earth's rotational axis), and even adjust their 3D design for their geography (it can be made more precise that way).

A sun-dial also tells another story: the history of time-telling. For thousands of years people have tried to make machines to tell the time - such as sundials, water clocks, candle clocks, hourglass and through to the more modern devices using gears, springs and weights, or today’s electronic and atomic clocks. Kids can learn about the ancient civilizations (the Romans, the Druids of Stonehenge etc.) based on how they told the time, and also learn about the history of technology as they see the progression from the ancient Egyptian sundials of 3,500 years ago to today’s atomic clocks.

description.text:
To fully understand the awesome device got to the wikipedia https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jefferson_disk page I will try to explain it here to the best of my abillity.

President Thomas Jefferson is famous for being the person who wrote the declaration of independence, a founding father, and a politician. Well it turns out he was actually an inventor and mathematician(who knew right!).
A while back I visited the National cytological museum. For those who don’t know it is a relatively small museum next to the NSA headquarters buildings. It is about the history of cypher and encryption from the revolutionary war to around the cold war. One of the exhibits in the revolutionary war and civil war section was about this device. This is where I got the inspiration from.
What really impresses me about this device is that the concept is so simple yet deciphering it is so hard if not close too impossible. The way it works is you turn the disks so that they say on one line the message you want. Then you put the rod through the holes to keep the wheels from turning independently. Rotate all of the disks to a different line and right the message it says there on a piece of paper. So that when the recipient gets the message s/he will turn the disks to say that message on the page and will turn all the disks to where the message is. In the letter not in the code you should write the order of the disks and how many lines away the real message is from your message.

The genius behind this can be revealed when looking at other simple ciphers that were introduced before it. For example, if you write the simplest cypher where each letter is represented by another letter or symbol. One can easily crack it by finding words like ‘a,’ ‘all,’ or ‘I’. since if you found a word in the message you were trying to decode that said ‘WMM’ it is almost certainly ‘all’ then you could change all ‘w’s to ‘a’ and all ‘m’s to ‘l’s and so on. Obviously this is not a very good code. Whereas here a single letter can be different every time so a word like ‘all’ would not be recognized.

Jefferson disk cipher: a history and math lesson in one!

Overview & Background:

A while back I visited the National cytological museum. For those who don’t know it is a relatively small museum next to the NSA headquarters buildings. It is about the history of cypher and encryption from the revolutionary war to around the cold war. One of the exhibits in the revolutionary war and civil war section was about this device. This is where I got the inspiration from.
What really impresses me about this device is that the concept is so simple yet deciphering it is so hard if not close too impossible. The way it works is you turn the disks so that they say on one line the message you want. Then you put the rod through the holes to keep the wheels from turning independently. Rotate all of the disks to a different line and right the message it says there on a piece of paper. So that when the recipient gets the message s/he will turn the disks to say that message on the page and will turn all the disks to where the message is. In the letter not in the code you should write the order of the disks and how many lines away the real message is from your message.
The genius behind this can be revealed when looking at other simple ciphers that were introduced before it. Obviously this is not a very good code. Whereas here a single letter can be different every time so a word like ‘all’ would not be recognized.
This concept is what the famous German enigma was based off of.

title: Eachine Gimbal mount for F450 quadcopter

description.text:
I was searching for a simple way to attach my gimbal to quadcopter so I came up with this design. You can see on images how it's mounted, yellow thing between printed parts is just a normal sponge for dish washing, I found out that it absorbs vibrations a lot better than black rubber on gimbal, so why not make an combination. Of course, sponge is glued with hot glue.

It's printed in PLA with 0.2mm layer height, slicer was simplify3D.
You can see that one part has metal inside, that's a bit catchy part, after 5mm you have to pause your print and insert metal part, after that just continue your print.
Infill is 30%
Gimbal I used is Eachine from Bangood, cheap and very good, and with this gimbal configuration works great, image is very steady.

title: H125 Micro Quad V1 -7mm/8.5mm Micro SciSky Based (under $50)

description.text:
Looking for an affordable trainer quad that you’ll still enjoy flying after you've mastered your moves? This H125 micro quad might be the right choice. Measuring just under 100mm long, about 75mm wide, and 125mm diagonally, this is the perfect medium-sized micro quad for just about every skill level and every age. Weighing in at just 45 grams fully-stuffed, including the battery! We've based this micro around the 7mm brushed motor because we've found that they’re inexpensive yet get the job done. Instead of using screws and aluminum spacers, the quad is designed around a peg system that saves a significant amount of weight and makes construction and repairs a snap. Using a Turnigy nanotech 260mah lipo, you will get about 4 1/2 minutes of flight time. If you want to see this quad fly check out our micro quad flight video. If you have any suggestions on how we can modify our design to make it better just leave a comment. If you are looking to make and easy remix, our designs are also publicly available on Onshape. Please refer to links included at the bottom of the page for specific links to our designs. If you like this project, make sure to check out our other cool science projects on our youtube page!

Want to easily customize and change this design, check out Onshape design to make a copy!

UPDATE (12/25/15): New squishy Ninjaflex feet to absorb the shock from rough landings!

UPDATE (1/11/17): New 8.5mm BETA frame released. Now includes top and bottom plates. Ninjaflex feet soon to come.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Use your default settings

Notes:

Top Plate: Print in PLA or ABS with no rafts or supports. Print with 4 shells and 15-20% infill. You may have to flip the design in your slicing program because of the LOSI slot.

Bottom Plate: Print in PLA or ABS WITHOUT rafts, but WITH supports. Print with 4 shells and 15-20% infill.

Spacer Pegs: Print in PLA or ABS with rafts and supports. Print with 3 shells and 100% infill. We suggest printing at least 4 at a time so that each peg has time to cool before another layer is added, ensuring that your pegs don't deform.

UPDATE (12/25/16): New design with squishy rubber Ninjaflex feet. These feet help absorb and disipate the impact when you have a rough landing. This requires a dual extruder printer capable of printing Ninjaflex. Use the same settings for all of the PLA/ABS parts, but print the Ninjaflex at 10-15% infil with two shells. There are four .STL files of the rubber feet. When dragged into your sclicer, make sure to reset their positions so that they align with the plastic base!

description.text:
Here is a direct drive version of the Neustruder. Its goals remain the same. Provide a cheap, accessable extruder that will provide excellent filament constriction for all or nearly all filaments. This is still a WIP and is subject to slight change, which should improve performance for all.

V1.5 is up! Sorry for the long period of no updates, I did alot of testing and eliminated the small PTFE tube for plug-and-play Printing! Tested with materials printing @ 260C without any problems!

Designed as a near drop in part for extruders using the Mk8-10 designs.
Can be printed out of any typical plastics. All testing has been done using PLA without issue, including tests without a fan or heatsink attatched to the part.

Should work for Replicator 2x's, other makerbots that use the same design, Flashforge, CTC, and most Prusa i3 printers out there.

https://youtu.be/RrYQYZnhPU8 - Video of the extruder printing itself out of PLA and then a TPU benchy at 60mm/s.

****Parts Needed****
---Printed---
(1) Lower Block
(1) Upper Block
(1) Axle
---Purchased---
(1) 604zz Bearing
(3) 35mm M3 Screws.
(2) 5-10mm M3 Screws
(3) M3 Nuts

Let me know of the problems you have or how I can improve the instructions to help. Happy printing!

Printer:

Either my Rigidbot or my Makerselect i3 V2 printed this well. Easily prints.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2mm or less

Infill:

25%+

Notes:

This is a part that works well printed fast but will get better results for you if you print it slow. If your printer is uncalibrated, it will come out sloppy but still work.

I print standing so that the screw holes are on the build plate and it is longest vertically.

Assembly Instructions

https://youtu.be/T2W6UJ_LzEg - Assembly Video

1) Reverse Orientation of the Stock extruder gear. Do not tighten as you will need to position as far away from the motor as possible.
2) Fasten Lower Block to the nema 17 with the two shorter (5-10mm) screws. It should be positioned closest to the connector on the stepper motor.
3) Position the gear so that the teeth are fully covering the filament opening through the block, while maximizing distance from the stepper motor.
4) Center the bearing on the axle
5) Put the axle with bearing into the slot in the upper block.
6) Place the upper block assembly with slot facing down so that the screw holes match between the upper and lower block.
7) Insert the nuts into their cutouts in the upper block
8) Insert the screws from the opposite side of the upper block and thread into the nuts. Do not tighten beyond fully threading

That is the fully assembled block.

To insert the filament, begin extruding filament, push the filament down into the hole, and then tighten screws equally (switch often) until filament begins extruding out of the hotend. After both (or three) screws are equally tightened after this process, complete one additional revolution of the screws. It should be sufficiently tight to extrude successfully. For Flexible filaments, two or three revolutions may be required to ensure sufficient grip.

You will need to remove filament using a reverse extrusion command, as there is no idler release, but it should come out without issue. Sometimes filament will get clogged on the teeth during this, increase your retraction speed when you're pulling it out and it should solve the problem.

DO NOT OVERTIGHTEN. YOU WILL HAVE A VERY BAD TIME.

Most of the problems people have had while using the bowden version is that they have over tightened the screws, meaning even very high-torque motors cannot turn (96in/oz)
This is why you start from 0 and tighten from there. Seriously, don't do it.

title: Dop Stick Holder for Lapidary Work

description.text:
This is intended to serve as a dop stick holder for lapidary work, but surely has application for holding other tools. The model has a ridge at the bottom of the holes, which is intended to be useful in retaining the orientation of a rod with a notch in the bottom, particularly for gemstone faceting.

The STL included has two rows of five holes, the holes are made for 1/2 inch sticks, and has the index in the bottom of the holes.

The SCAD file is parametric and will let you adjust the number of rows and columns of holes, the size of the holes, spacing between them, the height of the overall part, the depth of the hole, and whether or not it has the index in the bottom. Download the .scad file to make changes and export your own, or use customizer to make your changes.

To adapt large holes for smaller dop sticks, use the adapter over here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1705620

The printed holder pictured was printed in ProtoParadigm Woodchip ProSpec PLA.

This was made as part of a series featured here: http://www.protoparadigm.com/news-updates/what-to-do-with-a-3d-printer-make-lapidary-tools-and-accessories/

I find that even with good print settings some light stringing can occur across the opening, making it difficult to insert the blade.
